<TEXT>
the only way to stop poachers from 
killing elephants for their tusks is to take the fashion statement 
out of ivory kenyas leading wildlife official said 
a piece of paper which says you shall not trade in elephant 
ivory is about worth the paper its written on richard leakey 
said sunday at a benefit for friends of conservation 
the way to stop the trade in elephants is to make the people of 
the world disgusted and revolted by the wearing of animal parts 
particularly elephants 
leakey who became director of wildlife conservation in kenya in 
the spring has boosted the east african countrys efforts to save 
its elephant population 
earlier this year kenya was losing an average of 2 elephants 
every day from its national parks and reserves leakey said the 
countrys elephant population has dwindled during the last decade 
from 65000 to 17000 
leakey said that during the past four months poaching has 
virtually stopped because of a crackdown on poaching 
four people have been killed since july in attacks that leakey 
blamed on poachers who were frustrated by the drive he said 
friends of conservation was originally founded as friends of the 
masai mara in 1982 to preserve the wildlife and endangered habitat 
of the masai mara game reserve in kenya 
by 1987 the original project was expanded to help other regions 
in africa and the name was changed to friends of conservation the 
group has offices in oak brook ill london and nairobi 
