<TEXT>
here is a brief look at the major ethnic problems facing the 
soviet union as the communist party central committee prepares to 
meet this week to adopt new nationwide policies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
nagornokarabakh the predominantly armenian population wants 
control of this mountainous area to be transferred from 
traditionally moslem azerbaijan to christian armenia over the past 
18 months the dispute has led to 100 deaths in both republics and 
hundreds of thousands of people have fled their homes to quell the 
dispute the kremlin has imposed direct rule over the region 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
georgia the republic neighboring azerbaijan and armenia in the 
caucasus mountain region is beset by disputes between minority 
abkhazians demanding more autonomy and majority georgians there are 
also disputes among many other small ethnic groups soviet soldiers 
killed 20 people while breaking up a georgian nationalist 
demonstration in the capital of tbilisi in april 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fergana valley one hundred people were killed homes were 
torched and thousands evcuated from eastern uzbekistan in june in a 
pogrom aimed mostly at minority meskhetian turks who were forcibly 
resettled from georgia in the 1940s many say overcrowding and lack 
of jobs caused the situation to explode 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
baltics the three baltic republics lithuania latvia and 
estonia have been pressing the kremlin for greater autonomy they 
now want at minimum to serve as a laboratory for economic reform and 
at maximum to regain the independence they had before being 
incorporated into the soviet union in 1940 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ukraine a newly unified grassroots political movement the 
narodni rukh seeks to unify groups promoting political reform 
religious freedom and preservation of the ukrainian language and 
culture in the countrys secondlargest republic 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
moldavia moldavians won the battle to have their language 
declared the official one and to have the latin alphabet replace 
cyrillic in the republic bordering romania the move met stiff 
resistance from nonmoldavians who struck factories and offices 
the republic was incorporated by stalin in 1940 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ethnic germans thousands of ethnic germans who have retained 
their native language and culture despite having come to russia in 
czarist times are being allowed to emigrate to west germany once 
residents of a homeland on the volga river many were dispersed 
during world war ii to kazakhstan and other areas farther east 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kazakhstan president mikhail s gorbachevs ethnic problems 
broke into the open in december 1986 when the replacement of 
communist party chief dinmukhamed kunaev a kazakh with russian 
gennady kolbin sparked rioting a parliamentary committee is looking 
into claims that many more people died than the two reported 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
crimean tatars another group exiled by stalin from their 
homeland in the crimean peninsula the descendants of the mongols 
who terrorized medieval russia are clamoring to return home they 
carried out a noisy demonstration on red square in july 1987 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
nationalities of the far north scholars and activists say many 
very small ethnic groups of the far north are in danger of 
disappearing or having their cultures ruined by the encroachment of 
industrial development some groups have only a few thousand members 
</TEXT>
