<TEXT>
india and sri lanka today signed an 
agreement under which indian peacekeeping troops will leave this 
violencewracked island by the end of the year and begin observing a 
unilateral ceasefire this week 
the pact ends a threemonth diplomatic deadlock that at one point 
had threatened to escalate into an armed confrontation between the 
two countries 
new delhi sent about 47000 troops to sri lanka in july 1987 to 
supervise a peace accord that offered separatist rebels from the 
ethnic tamil minority limited autonomy if they would lay down their 
weapons 
the tamils were urged to end their fight for an independent 
homeland in the north and east provinces and offered limited 
autonomy 
but the largest tamil group liberation tigers of tamil eelam 
rejected the accord and began attacking the indian troops at least 
1000 of whom have since been killed 
the presence of indian soldiers and the government peace offer to 
the tamils also triggered a bloody backlash by militants of the 
islands ethnic sinhalese majority 
they argued that sinhalesedominated government had offered too 
many concessions to the minority tamils and had compromised the 
nations sovereignty by inviting indian soldiers to sri lankan soil 
in an effort to curb ethnic violence that has claimed more than 
16000 lives in the past six years sri lankan president ranasinghe 
premadasa demanded that the indian troops leave the island by july 
29 the date was the second anniversary of the signing of the peace 
accord signed by premadasas predecessor junius r jayewardene 
but indian prime minister rajiv gandhi refused saying a hasty 
withdrawal could lead to even greater bloodshed that triggered a 
diplomatic deadlock that at one point threatened to snowball into 
war 
a military showdown however was averted when india agreed to 
make a token withdrawal on july 29 and limited pullouts 
subsequently at least 3000 troops have returned home 
the two countries worked out a timetable for the withdrawal of 
the remaining 42000 soldiers earlier this month at the meeting of 
nonaligned nations in yugoslavia 
a government communique on the agreement said india has 
assured that all effort will made made to complete by dec 31 1989 
 
it said indian soldiers will suspend military operations against 
the tamil rebels beginning at 6 am wednesday it said tamil 
rebels had earlier expressed a willingness to a cessation of 
hostilities on a reciprocal basis 
the agreement also said the sri lankan army commander and the 
commanding officer of the indian troops would monitor possible 
ceasefire violations and report them to premadasa 
meanwhile in the northeast indian soldiers were involved in a 
major searchanddestroy operation in which 40 tamil rebels were 
killed and 28 wounded according to a statement by the indian high 
commission or embassy 
at least five indian soldiers were killed and 16 wounded in the 
operation that began tuesday the statement said 
the tamil secession began in 1983 with complaints of 
discrimination in jobs and education by the sinhalesedominated 
government 
sinhalese most of whom are buddhists make up 75 percent of the 
population and control the government and the military tamils are 
predominantly buddhists 
india became involved in the ethnic problems of its southeastern 
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million tamils to 
the rebel cause 
