<TEXT>
some officials said monday that indias 
decision to withdraw its troops from sri lanka could help end ethnic 
violence that has killed 16000 people but others feared it might 
result in a bloodbath 
according to an agreement signed monday in colombo india will 
withdraw its 42000 peacekeeping troops from the island by the end 
of the year breaking a threemonth diplomatic deadlock between the 
two south asian neighbors 
the troops stationed in sri lanka to enforce a 1987 peace 
accord also will begin observing a unilateral ceasefire in their 
campaign against tamil militants at 6 am wednesday the agreement 
said 
in new delhi a foreign ministry spokesman was optimistic the 
agreement would work because it accommodated each others 
interests and concerns 
a leader of the moderate sinhalese liberal party welcomed the 
agreement as a step toward ending spiraling violence it sounds 
like at last we might see an end to the violence because this is a 
starting point to get all forces into the democratic process said 
chanaka amaratunga 
the agreement also said the sri lankan army commander and the 
commanding officer of the indian troops will monitor possible 
ceasefire violations and report them to sri lankan president 
ranasinghe premadasa 
a moderate tamil leader feared the withdrawal of indian troops 
would lead to a security vacuum and cause a bloodbath 
will there be a professional police force capable of commanding 
the confidence of all people in the north and east because only 
such a force can prevent a bloodbath scenario once the indian troops 
leave said the leader who spoke on condition of anonymity 
india deployed more than 50000 troops to sri lanka in july 1987 
to supervise a peace accord that offered tamil rebels limited 
autonomy if they laid down their weapons and ended their campaign 
for an independent homeland in the northern and eastern provinces of 
the island nation 
but the largest and most militant rebel group the liberation 
tigers of tamil eelam rejected the accord because it did not 
fulfill their expectations and turned their guns against indian 
troops 
the presence of indian troops also caused a bloody backlash by 
sinhalese militants extremists of the sinhalese peoples liberation 
front opposed the government for signing the accord that offered too 
many concessions to the tamils they also resented the presence of 
indian troops on the island as a threat to national sovereignty 
tamils who are mostly hindu form 18 percent of the countrys 16 
million people and claim they are discriminated against in jobs and 
education by members of the sinhalese community who are mostly 
buddhist and comprise 75 percent of the population dominating the 
government and military 
at least 11000 people including 1000 indian troops have been 
killed since the tamil insurgency started in 1983 another 5000 
have died in the sinhalese backlash 
in an effort to curb ethnic violence that has ripped across the 
onceidyllic palmfringed indian ocean island premadasa demanded 
indian troops leave by july 29 the second anniversary of the 
signing of the indosri lankan peace accord but indian prime 
minister rajiv gandhi refused saying a hasty withdrawal could lead 
to greater bloodshed 
india made a token withdrawal on july 29 and then made gradual 
pullouts it finalized a schedule for withdrawal of the remaining 
troops at the meeting of nonaligned nations earlier this month in 
yugoslavia 
a peace committee consisting of members of political and ethnic 
groups in the northeastern province will be formed to settle local 
administrative issues under mondays agreement 
a security coordination group also will be set up to ensure law 
and order in the northeastern province it will include the sri 
lankan minister of state for defense the defense secretary and the 
commander of the indian peacekeeping troops 
