<TEXT>
researchers using the first approved transfer 
of a foreign gene into humans said monday that altered 
cancerfighting cells have shrunk tumors in one patient and that 
cells from a single injection continue to work for at least 19 days 
dr steven a rosenberg a national cancer institute researcher 
said that five patients all terminally ill with a cancer called 
maglignant melanoma have been treated with genemodified cells but 
he could report on only one patient a 26yearold woman 
that patient he said suffers from melanoma that had formed 
tumors throughout her body including the lungs the skin and the 
soft palate of the mouth 
in july she received an infusion of a type of cancerfighting 
cell called genemodified tumorinfiltrating lymphocytes rosenberg 
said later tests showed that the tumor in her mouth had 
regressed or shrunk by about 90 percent 
the lymphocytes used in the study are natural cancerfighting 
cells that had been cultured from cells withdrawn from the womans 
tumors rosenberg and his colleagues have developed a technique 
wherein tumorinfiltrating lymphocytes or til cells are cultured 
in the laboratory in interleukin2 a protein that promotes 
lymphocyte growth when the cells multiply to 200 billion they are 
then reinjected into the patients blood stream as an army of cancer 
fighters 
rosenberg reported last year that this technique resulted in a 50 
percent tumor reduction in at least 60 percent of the treated 
patients 
cells used in the latest study were further manipulated so that 
the researchers could trace the movement of the til cells in the 
patients bodies to mark the tils the researchers inserted into 
the cells a neomycinresistant gene the gene manipulated through 
the use of a mouse leukemia retrovirus a virus that can move genes 
from one type of cell to another is the first foreign or 
nonhuman gene to be approved for use in patient therapy 
rosenberg said that in the female patient the researchers were 
able to recover some of the marked cells from several sites proving 
that the cancerfighting cells did migrate to the tumors he said 
the study also showed that the cells lived for at least 19 days and 
that followup studies may show that the cells live even longer 
additionally rosenberg said that there have been no side 
effects to the introduced cells in any patient 
he called the results extremely preliminary 
all five patients who have received the genemodified 
cancerfighting cells are still alive he said the therapy will be 
attempted soon on another five patients 
eventually rosenberg said the genemanipulation technique may 
be used to introduce into the cancerfighting cell a gene for 
another type of lymphocyte thus making the til cell an even 
stronger cancerfighter 
rosenberg made the comments at a news conference that followed a 
report to a meeting monday of the national cancer advisory board a 
group appointed by the president to monitor federal cancer research 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

