<TEXT>
the head of the federal agency that studies the 
air and oceans said monday that climatic change is likely over the 
next century and that there are no quick or easy answers to the 
problem 
we can recycle we can conserve we can change our lifestyle 
but i believe it is unrealistic to expect that population and 
energy use can continue to grow without adding humaninduced 
climatic change to the normal variability of nature said john 
knauss head of the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
knauss spoke at a conference on earth observation and global 
change held to discuss research efforts into the causes of the 
problem and to seek solutions 
do not expect easy answers and do not expect quick results i 
expect in the next hundred years and more we will go through a 
significant human induced climate change said knauss 
climatic change particularly the socalled greenhouse warming 
effect have attracted considerable attention in recent years 
many scientists believe that carbon dioxide added to the 
atmosphere by industry and other human activities could trap heat 
from the sun and induce a catastrophic global overheating in the 
next century 
carbon dioxide a colorless odorless gas has increased by 25 
percent over the last 100 years a change blamed on industrial 
processes that produce the chemical and on the destruction of 
forests which remove carbon dioxide from the air 
other scientists urge more study however wondering if increased 
cloudiness or other natural factors might prevent much of the feared 
warming 
both sides seem to agree that it is too soon to measure any 
actual greenhouseinduced warming because changes in yeartoyear 
weather normally vary so widely 
leonard fisk of the national aeronautics and space administration 
told the conference that his agency is launching a major mission 
to planet earth to help answer some of the questions about global 
change 
william f harris of the national science foundation added that 
the organization also is promoting such research and noted that the 
federal committee on earth science recently announced a coordinated 
global change research effort by a dozen federal agencies 
but knauss admonished listeners not to look for too much too fast 
he said that what concerns him even more than the threat of 
change is that many problems such as the hole in the protective 
ozone layer found over antarctica have come as surprises 
greenhouse warming was first predicted three decades ago he 
noted but scientists were surprised by the ozone hole by recent 
reports of increased methane in the air and by a rise in lowlevel 
ozone in rural areas 
my concern in this context is not so much on what their effect 
is on global change or the environment which is real but that we 
did not predict them it is not much of an exaggeration to say we 
almost stumbled over them said knauss 
i continue to ask myself what is it that were not measuring 
that we should be measuring he added 
</TEXT>
