rafael m estevezs hobby again became his 
work monday when hurricane hugo cut communications in the caribbean 
turning ham radio operators into key sources of information for the 
islands 
during such emergencies his home serves as base for a network of 
ham radio operators helping people contact relatives and relaying 
emergency information 
i like this because i can help my community my friends and 
people i dont know estevez said 
when hugo left communications dependent on estevez and other ham 
radio operators reporters descended on his home and television 
camera cables snaked through his front door and across the living 
room floor 
estevez seated at a desk topped with ham radio equipment and two 
telephones gave live broadcasts in spanish for several television 
stations on the latest damage reports from notes he had jotted on a 
pad 
in the community of arroyo on puerto ricos southeastern coast 
the mayor and several dozen other people stayed in a 
theaterturnedshelter after hugo passed because most homes were 
destroyed and power lines lying in the streets made travel 
dangerous estevez reported 
a huge wave about 30 feet high reportedly struck the villages 
beach he said 
the islands of vieques and culebra off the eastern end of puerto 
rico were severely pounded by hugo with wind reported up to 135 
mph he said 
theres a lot of roofless houses he said 
estevez is president and founder of the international society of 
radio amateurs with members in central america and south america 
plaques on his wall praise the groups work including transmitting 
information during the united states invasion of grenada 
estevez works at hialeah park race track taking bets and does 
racetrack publicity for the spanishspeaking media but said he is 
excused from work during emergencies like hugo 
a fellow ham radio operator robert pastor fielded phone calls 
while pressing estevez to eat a late lunch 
estevez 50 recalled other disasters including the 1972 
nicaraguan earthquake he said radio operators serve as a vital link 
for people trying to contact relatives in disasterstruck areas 
earthquakes you get more victims than hurricanes he said 
hurricanes you get less victims but more damage 
ham radio operator bernard bob sternberg of sunrise also 
relayed information monday he said he transmitted assistance 
requests for the eastern caribbean island of montserrat to the red 
cross in washington and talked to a st croix ham radio operator 
who described utter destruction on that island 
sternberg said he spoke early monday to a ham radio operator on a 
boat anchored in a mangrove swamp at vieques he said the operator 
told him there was no wind no rain and he knew he was in the eye 
of the storm and said he was making preparations for the full 
brunt of the hurricane 
he asked us to pray for him and we did sternberg said we 
prayed for all of them 
