<DOCNO> AP890918-0178 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
gen michel aoun who serves as lebanons 
president and calls himself its savior works eats and sleeps in a 
command bunker two floors under a presidential palace crumpled by 
syrian artillery fire 
from there he holds out in the war of his christian forces 
against the powerful syrians and their allies pledging to save 
lebanon or whats left of it even if it means the destruction of 
beirut 
the syrians have made life unbearable for my people and im 
going to make life equally unbearable for them in lebanon he said 
in a recent interview in the bunker 
syrian artillery has systematically reduced the twostory hilltop 
palace in the christian suburb of baabda to wreckage since fighting 
erupted march 8 into another fierce round of lebanons 14yearold 
civil war 
the 54yearold general has rarely ventured out of the spartan 
bunker since he launched his war of liberation against the 
syrians 
aides say aoun a small pudgy man always clad in fatigues lives 
on a daily diet of beans rice and potatoes occasionally a steak 
he works an 18hour day rising every morning at 6am for a 
brief period of exercises 
his wife nadia and three daughters mireille claudine and 
chantal stayed with him in the bunker in the initial weeks of the 
fighting but he has sent them to the family home in the mountains 
for safety 
the generals critics call him napolaoun hinting that his 
lopsided war against the syrians who with their allies outnumber 
his forces by at least 3 to 1 stem from delusions of grandeur 
president hafez assad of syria his plan to pacify lebanon 
thwarted by aouns campaign angrily calls the christian leader that 
mad little general 
but to most of the 1 million christians trapped for the last six 
months in their enclave north of beirut by the syrians aoun is a 
hero 
they consider him the first lebanese leader to stand up to the 
syrians 
despite savage artillery battles in which more than 900 people 
have been killed and nearly 2700 wounded many of them christian 
civilians aoun is unbending in the belief that his crusade is right 
this war needs sacrifice and patience he said no one 
wages a war and promises paradise but i believe i have the support 
of the people 
a maronite catholic aoun is the lebanese army commander 
although fewer than half the armys 42000 soldiers support him 
most of the armys moslem units have defected and set up their own 
command but stayed out of the fighting 
about 10000 soldiers have remained loyal to aoun and he is 
highly popular with them 
he bridles at being called the christians leader insisting he 
is a national lebanese leader a patriot fighting for christians and 
moslems alike 
he notes with pride that his men include some 3000 sunni moslems 
aouns campaign has made him a prime target for assassination 
six lebanese were arrested in cyprus in may on a mission to shoot 
down his helicopter with missiles when he flew to the mediterranean 
island en route to an arab summit in morocco as it turned out he 
never left beirut 
aides say that aoun sleeps with a pistol under his pillow in his 
bunker and has a deep fear of car bombs a favored method of 
assassination in lebanon 
in 1983 unidentified gunmen shot up his motorcade wounding him 
in the head and arm the following year his men discovered a car 
bomb in beirut only minutes before his motorcade was due to pass 
one western military attache called him the best officer the 
lebanese army has ever produced 
while few question his courage in lebanons long civil war they 
say hes out of his depth in the world of politics but even moslem 
officers say aouns personal integrity is beyond reproach 
they noted that when the israelis moved into west beirut in 1982 
they asked him to send troops into the palestinian refugee camps of 
sabra and chatilla 
he refused the rightwing lebanese forces the christians main 
militia went in instead and killed hundreds of palestinians 
aoun always wanted to be a soldier he entered lebanons military 
academy when he was 20 and graduated three years later as an 
artillery lieutenant 
he was named army commander in june 1984 at the age of 49 the 
youngest since lebanon gained independence from france in 1943 
aoun was wounded three times in 198384 when as a colonel he 
commanded the strategic mountaintop town of souk elgharb southeast 
of beirut against syrianbacked militia forces who had driven the 
christians out of the mountains 
his men repulsed six major assaults losing 400 dead 
aoun had hoped that when he took on the syrians this time the 
united states would support him but washington has stayed on the 
sidelines 
the united states withdrew the last of its diplomats from beirut 
on sept 6 after aoun accused the americans of betraying him 
</TEXT>
