<TEXT>
edythe pahl is director of the certified 
financial planning professional education program at the college for 
financial planning and holds an mba and a fellow in life management 
institute an insurance organization 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the recent publicity about longterm care insurance 
policies and the stories of families devastated by the burgeoning 
costs of nursing home care bring to mind fears of becoming a burden 
to our loved ones 
this scenario never has to play if we learn more about longterm 
care itself and the resources available to cover the risks of not 
having enough information education and careful planning will 
eliminate the fears usually associated with long stays in nursing 
homes 
what is longterm care it has been described as medical 
personal or social services provided at a nursing home a custodial 
facility at home or at a community program for a year or longer a 
longterm care insurance policy is designed to cover most of the 
expenses associated with these services but that are not covered by 
medicare medicaid or medigap policies 
why is there so much publicity about longterm care there are 
three major influences at work that have focused attention on the 
issue 
the first is the growing number of americans over age 65 it is 
expected that by 2020 20 percent of our population will be 
seniors 
the second is a dramatic change in the definition of family 
two working parents fewer children per family more people without 
children more divorces more families living in geographically 
diverse locations all of this equals fewer resources available for 
extended care at home 
finally medicare accounts for less than 4 percent of extended 
care benefits under the old and new laws medicare does not pay for 
custodial nursing home care yet a recent study shows that 90 
percent of nursing home patients need only custodial care usually 
defined as care that meets personal needs such as getting out of 
bed walking eating or bathing professional skills or training 
are not required of the caregiver the other social healthcare 
program medicaid is intended only for the indigent 
so for most of us private resources must be available for both 
the patient and the patients family so neither will end up 
financially destitute 
before you research financing possible longterm care three 
steps should be taken first evaluate whether you think you will 
need longterm care in the future your familys medical history may 
give you clues did your forebears generally die young have your 
grandparents lived long healthy active lives 
next answer these questions dealing with your extended family 
are they willing to care for you at home would they refuse to let a 
family member stay in a nursing home are there resources to cover 
professional home health care is the family so displaced that there 
is no possibility of home care what kind of decisions would your 
family make about longterm care if you were incapable of making 
that choice finally consider the possibility that all your assets 
could be depleted by a stay of two years five years or longer 
the average cost of a years stay in a nursing home today is 
approximately 24000 using an inflation rate of 5 percent that 
annual cost will be almost 40000 in only 10 years knowing this 
now means that some of your assets can be invested specifically for 
such a purpose if you need it for longterm care its there if 
you dont it becomes a part of your estate 
longterm care insurance policies then are not the only answer 
but the efficiencies of a longterm care policy may prove to be the 
best course 
finding the right policy is no simple matter products are 
complicated and expensive each seems to offer the perfect solution 
the number of companies offering these types of policies is 
increasing rapidly which means competition will continue to 
increase benefits for the consumers but it also means you must 
examine the details and fine print 
the best advice now may be to wait a while if you can perhaps a 
year or two while the marketplace sorts out the best policies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890918-0215 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
jane weston wilson is the author of the lifestyle 
cookbook eating well when you just cant eat the way you used 
to workman publishing 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
my favorite summer month to visit friends is 
september in resort towns the crowds have gone but the water is 
still warm enough to swim 
its the perfect time for the unforgettable barbecue at the 
beach fish bought at dockside sweet corn in husks to share the 
grill and tomatoes to eat outofhand bought en route from a farm 
stand 
in september when i visit friends in suburban and country 
settings what i find is more and more of their garden space is 
given over to the growing of vegetables too which reach their 
zenith now magenta beets rosy turnips purple egglants red and 
green peppers yellow squash and whiteribbed collard greens are all 
flourishing 
not since the victory gardens of world war ii where i remember 
growing vegetables with schoolmates in a nearby vacant lot have we 
as a nation been so enthusiastic about growing our own weve 
learned squarefoot gardening circle gardening and 
container gardening all for the purpose of using our space 
efficiently whether in my twobytwofoot plot in a manhattan urban 
garden between two highrisers or in a great big 200foot country 
backyard 
as edible landscapes pop up all over the country and local 
farmers through the green farm project bring their vegetables and 
fruits to cities and towns libraries and bookstore shelves are 
becoming crowded with books that encourage taking creative 
responsibility for our environment and ourselves the friends i 
visit in congers ny to celebrate their annual september harvest 
feast are two of the best examples i know of treating themselves and 
their environment with the utmost of respect 
joan is a professor of nutrition at columbia teachers college 
alan who is an artist by profession is national president of earth 
day surrounding the house where they raised their family is a 
vegetable garden and small orchard that has evolved as their 
commitment has grown to the environment here they produce food that 
feeds them handsomely yearround in a totally natural cycle without 
pesticides 
the lucky guests invited on this special sunday choose the 
vegetables they want to prepare and cook for each course pole beans 
for a crips nosh to eat in the garden leaning into a hoe to turn up 
small potatoes reaching for kale that is the size of a small tree 
to make into the hearty portuguese caldo verde soup armfuls of 
eggplants peppers leeks onions tomatoes zucchini and basil to 
turn into a glorious ratatouille 
laughter and good conversation abound as we reach for pots take 
our turns at the stove serve each course at the kitchen table until 
the last delicious morsel of fruit cobbler is eaten by candlelight 
in the lengthening evening 
here are some favorites 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
5 pounds fresh tomatoes rinsed 
boiling water as needed 
3 tbl olive oil 
2 cloves garlic finely chopped 
1 cup chopped fresh basil 
4 quarts of water 
1 tsp olive oil 
 
1 place the tomatoes in a very large kettle and cover them with 
boiling water as soon as the skins begin to break remove the 
tomatoes with a slotted spoon peel the skins from the tomatoes and 
core working in batches place the skinned tomatoes in a blender 
and whirl until they are small chunks 
2 in a large saucepan over mediumhigh heat heat the 3 
tablespoons of oil add the garlic and saute until translucent 1 to 
2 minutes add the tomatoes and basil and bring to a boil stirring 
constantly reduce the heat and simmer stirring occasionally for 
10 minutes use at once or let the sauce cool and refrigerate 
covered until serving time or when cooled freeze in boilable 
plastic freezer bags 
yield 1 quart 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
1 small eggplant trimmed unpeeled and cut into 1inch cubes 
2 mediumsized yellow onions peeled and cut lengthwise into 
eighths 
2 large leeks white parts only thoroughly rinsed halved 
lengthwise and sliced crosswise into inch slices 
1 summer squash trimmed cut lengthwise into thirds and then 
into inch cubes 
1 sweet green pepper seeded and cut into inchthick rings 
1 sweet red pepper seeded and cut into inchthick rings 
1 pound fresh tomatoes chopped 
4 tbl olive oil or corn oil 
4 cloves garlic finely chopped 
3 tbl chopped fresh basil or 1 tbl dried basil 
1 tbl dried oregano 
tsp each of dried leaf thyme and fennel seeds 
 
1 preheat oven to 350 degrees 
2 in a large baking dish or casserole combine the vegetables 
and pour on the oil and seasonings mix thoroughly until all 
vegetables are well coated 
3 cover and bake in the preheated 350degree oven for 35 to 45 
minutes until tender but the vegetables should retain their shapes 
stir often the vegetables will release a lot of liquid 
4 remove from the oven cool slightly and serve cold or at room 
temperature 
</TEXT>
