<TEXT>
the census bureau and the national council on 
the aging are joining forces to recruit older americans for some of 
the 480000 temporary jobs that will be created by next years 
national head count 
most of the workers will be out calling on people knocking on 
doors and finding out why they didnt return their census forms 
said census deputy director c louis kincannon others will have 
supervisory and office jobs 
most jobs will run six to eight weeks paying 5 to 8 an hour 
depending on location people with management experience will be key 
recruits for the office manager jobs which may pay more and last 
longer than doortodoor positions 
older people who are retired and have additional needs may find 
this an avenue that may give them a new sense of confidence and also 
demonstrate to a subsequent employer that theyve got it in them 
kincannon said 
older people would be ideal local censustakers because many have 
a lifetime attachment to their neighborhood which will help 
particularly in areas throught the country where youve had 
undercounts for instance in rural areas said donald l davis 
vice president of the ncoa 
most of the doortodoor jobs will be available next april and 
may while office positions could start earlier and last eight 
months to a year 
those interested should contact state employment offices or the 
nearest census bureau office recruitment for management and 
administrative jobs began this month ads and recruitment for 
outdoor jobs will start in february 
workers will have to pass a written test of basic abilities to 
work with numbers and read and follow instructions and most will 
need access to a car 
a new law lets federal postal and military retirees take 
temporary census jobs without loss of retirement pay or benefits 
the law lets federal retirees work shortterm census jobs without 
loss of benefits if total employment does not exceed six months and 
extend beyond dec 31 1990 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
an experimental pacemaker that 
adjusts the heart rate to meet the bodys needs has been implanted 
in four patients at jfk medical center where the first clinical 
studies of the device will be made 
the new design may make life easier for many of the 110000 
people annually who need a pacemaker to regulate their heart beats 
said dr paul winokur the thoracic surgeon who implanted the 
matchbooksized devices 
unlike conventional pacemakers set at a continuous rate the 
adaptable pacemaker monitors the nervous system to determine whether 
to speed up or slow down the heart rate 
we think its the next best thing to sliced bread winokur 
said we think its a great advance but its too early to say 
the us food and drug administration approved the metabolic 
pacemaker for clinical studies on aug 14 
winokur implanted the first one in 78yearold floyd cooper of 
lake worth three days later i feel great i really do cooper 
said 
a healthy heart reacts to the bodys need for blood by monitoring 
the nervous system the metabolic pacemaker tries to mimic a normal 
heart by using a sensor in the hearts right ventricle to report 
changing needs 
the sensor monitors respiration blood temperature and changes in 
the heartbeat to determine how much blood the body needs 
conventional pacemakers dont respond to demands from the body so 
too much activity or stress can result in weakness or fatigue 
winokur said 
clinical studies have been under way in europe for several months 
but jfk medical center is the only us hospital to use the 
pacemaker doctors said in coming months a few centers around the 
country will be selected to participate in the studies said barbara 
westrum of the st paul minnbased cardiac pacemakers inc which 
developed the pacemaker over the last 15 years 
if clinical studies show the pacemaker is effective it could be 
widely available within 18 months westrum said he estimated that 
up to 30 percent of pacemaker users will be able to use the new 
design it costs about 6000 some 500 more than conventional 
pacemakers 
</TEXT>
