<TEXT>
cocoa futures prices fell to new lifeofcontract lows monday on 
new yorks coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange following the 
international cocoa cartels failure to salvage a derailed 
pricesupport scheme 
on other markets grain and soybean futures fell sharply 
livestock and meat futures were mixed precious metals were lower 
and energy futures were mixed 
cocoa futures settled 54 to 67 lower with the contract for 
delivery in december at 1035 per metric ton all contracts 
established new lifetime lows 
the price drop followed the conclusion saturday of a fruitless 
sixday meeting in london of the international cocoa organization 
whose approximately 40 nationmembers were seeking to resolve 
problems that have severely weakened the cartels ability to support 
cocoa prices 
the icco charged with stabilizing world cocoa prices by 
maintaining a variable buffer stock of the commodity has been 
virtually powerless since february 1988 when the stockpile reached 
its permitted 250000metricton limit 
the organization also has been weakened by the refusal of some 
the major cocoa producers to pay levies on their cocoa exports to 
finance icco operations 
the overall debt to the organization by its 12 producer members 
now stands at 120 million cocoa producers say they cannot afford 
the levies due partly to the historically low price that cocoa 
commands in a world market burdened by five straight years of 
expanding supplies 
negotiators for the producer nations appeared to nearing a 
unified position at the london meeting on friday prompting hope for 
a solution to the iccos problems and the meeting was extended 
through saturday but discord ultimately prevailed said arthur 
stevenson a cocoa market analyst with prudentialbache securities 
inc in new york 
some of the participants at the end didnt even bother to vote 
they just walked out he said this means the international 
cocoa organization cannot be viewed as even a psychological 
pricesupport instrument because it is just not getting support from 
its key members 
further selling was prompted by indications that a proposed sale 
of 500000 metric tons of cocoa from the ivory coast the worlds 
largest producer to the trade house philipp brothers inc had 
fallen through 
grain and soybean futures fell sharply on the chicago board of 
trade due to harvest pressure and a report the soviet union will 
import no more grain in 1989 
