<TEXT>
stanford university and the university of 
southern california are targets of a federal probe into whether 
private colleges and universities are violating antitrust laws in 
the setting of tuition and financial aid officials said monday 
the two california universities were asked in recent days to 
forward documents to the us justice department signaling that an 
inquiry that once focused on colleges in the east and midwest had 
been broadened to include california schools 
federal officials said they were looking into whether private 
colleges and universities had engaged in a form of pricefixing by 
comparing notes with other schools before setting tuition and 
determining how much financial aid a student should receive 
officials at other private colleges and universities failed to 
immediately respond to requests for comment and it was unknown 
whether other california schools were targets of the federal probe 
the probe comes as private colleges face increasing pressure to 
justify tuition increases which have far outpaced inflation among 
the highranking officials who have complained about the increases 
is white house chief of staff john sununu the father of eight 
including two in college 
the justice departments antitrust division last week sent 
stanford a civil investigative demand for documents pertaining to 
financial aid and tuition said john schwartz the universitys 
legal counsel 
university provost james rosse said in a statement monday the 
school was complying with the governments request but stanford was 
innocent of any wrongdoing 
stanford has had a policy for many years that forbids exchange 
of current tuition student aid and salary information prior to the 
decisionmaking based on that data he said we are confident 
that the investigation will show our policy to have been effective 
the government has asked stanford and other schools for written 
answers to five questions on how the schools determine tuition and 
scholarships the government also asked for information on expenses 
ranging from travel to salaries along with telephone records 
rosse said the governments request will generate considerable 
legal expense 
christian markey general counsel for usc also confirmed the 
justice department recently asked for financial aid and tuition 
documents but declined further comment 
although stanford officials denied exchanging information prior 
to making tuition decisions undergraduate tuition at stanford and 
usc for the 198990 academic year fall within only a few hundred 
dollars of each other and are similar to tuitions at other 
california colleges 
stanford this year is charging 13569 and usc is charging 
