<TEXT>
delta air lines may join the combined 
computerized reservations system of northwest airlines and trans 
world airlines the three carriers announced monday 
discussions to combine the pars system owned jointly by northwest 
parent nwa inc and twa with deltas datas ii system are in the 
preliminary stages the airlines said plans call for the combined 
reservations system to operate as an autonomous company with 
independent management 
the announcement was no surprise to industry analysts and travel 
agents who expected delta to rebound from its failed bid to merge 
its reservations system with industryleader saber owned by 
american airlines parent amr corp plans for that merger were 
dropped after the justice department threatened to file an antitrust 
suit 
the federal agency said the joint operation would harm 
competition in the computerized sale of airline tickets 
robert decker an analyst for duff amp phelps inc in chicago said 
a merger of pars and deltas data ii would be less likely to draw 
justice department opposition because pars is much smaller than 
saber which has 41 percent of the nationwide market of the five 
systems used by airlines and travel agents 
pars is a distant fourth decker said and delta is interested in 
joining it because the data ii system is technologically inferior 
investing in a new system would be too costly he said 
delta has pretty well admitted they dont want to be a 
contender in computerized reservations decker said 
pars was started by twa and joined by northwest about three years 
ago 
dan mcelroy a partner and financial officer of travel 
professionals a travel agency in bloomington said pars is 
primarily known as a pocket player in the computerized ticketing 
industry it is strong in twa and northwest hubs and weak where the 
airlines dont have a presence he said 
deltas participation in pars could add another 2000 to 3000 
travel agencies now carrying the datas ii system mcelroy said 
ivar sigveland of travel professionals which has a pars system 
said there would be no immediate effect on consumers if the merger 
is completed but he said further consolidation in the ticketing 
industry might result in higher costs for travel agents 
you just dont know what the longterm effects are going to be 
when you lose that competition sigveland said 
reservations systems make money from fees charged to airlines 
for instance when a travel agent using a pars system books a flight 
for an american airlines customer american pays pars nearly 2 a 
flight segment decker said a onestop flight consists of two 
segments 
the computer systems the primary channel for the distribution of 
airline tickets provide uptotheminute information about 
schedules fares seat availability hotels car rentals and package 
vacations 
despite a 1986 regulation that says airlines must not favor their 
own flights in computer listings travel agents tend to be more 
loyal to the owner of the system they are using decker said 
